Data Collection: Gather data on user interactions, such as page views, time spent on pages, likes, and comments. This data will serve as the training set for your model.

Feature Engineering: Identify and engineer features relevant to content recommendation, such as user demographics, past content interactions, and contextual information about the content (e.g., tags, categories).

Model Selection: Choose appropriate machine learning algorithms for recommendation systems. Popular choices include collaborative filtering, content-based filtering, and hybrid approaches. Libraries like Scikit-Learn, TensorFlow, or PyTorch can be used to implement these models.

Training and Testing: Train your model on the collected data, validate its accuracy, and fine-tune parameters to improve performance. Use a hold-out set or cross-validation techniques to test the model’s effectiveness.

Implementation: Integrate the trained model into your website’s backend. This integration should dynamically use the model to make real-time recommendations to users based on their current and past interactions.

Feedback Loop: Implement mechanisms to capture user feedback on recommended content to refine and retrain your model periodically.

